ew-trad-music-star-is-born-zrhw33n8q|title=Sib\u00e9al N\u00ed Chasaide \u2014 a new trad music star is born|first=Lauren|last=Murphy|date=28 July 2019|via=www.thetimes.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n===Songs===\n* \"The Parting Glass\" (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-parting-glass-mw0003241354/releases|title=The Parting Glass - Sib\u00e9al N\u00ed Chasaide &#124; Releases|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n* \"Human\" (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/human-mw0003249949/releases|title=Human - Sib\u00e9al N\u00ed Chasaide &#124; Releases|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n* Traditional: Carrickfergus (arr. Pacey) (2019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/traditional-carrickfergus-arr-pacey-mw0003237071/releases|title=Traditional: Carrickfergus (arr. Pacey) - Sib\u00e9al N\u00ed Chasaide, Voces8 &#124; Releases|website=AllMusic}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=L6bENmhvxpk Clip of Sibeal Ni Chasaide - \"Mise \u00c9ire\" | The Late Late Show | RT\u00c9 One]\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.sibealofficial.com/}}\n* {{IMDb name}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ni Chasaide, Sibeal}}\n[[Category:Irish singers]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish singers]]\n[[Category:People from County Meath]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Irish-language singers]]\n\n\n{{Ireland-singer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Greyjoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sib%C3%A9al_N%C3%AD_Chasaide"}
{"title_page": "Murder of Gabriel Fernandez", "text_new": "{{short description|2013 murder of an abused eight-year-old American boy}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = Murder of Gabriel Fernandez\n| image                    =\n| caption                  =\n| date                     = {{start date|2013|05|22}} (fatal beating)<br>{{start date|2013|05|24}} (death)\n| time                     =\n| place                    = [[Palmdale, California]], U.S.\n| coordinates              =\n| motive                   = Possibly [[homophobia]]\n| type                     = [[Child abuse]], [[child neglect]]\n| arrests                  = Pearl Fernandez, Isauro Aguirre\n| convicted                = Fernandez, Aguirre\n| sentence                 = [[Life imprisonment]] without [[parole]] (Fernandez) <br /> [[Capital punishment in California|Death]] (Aguirre)\n| charges                  = [[First degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture (both defendents)\n| verdict                  =\n}}\n'''Gabriel Fernandez''' (February 20, 2005 \u2013 May 24, 2013) was an eight-year-old American boy from [[Palmdale, California]], who was abused and tortured over a period of months that ultimately ended in his fatal beating on May 22, 2013. His mother, Pearl Fernandez, and her boyfriend, Isauro Aguirre, were both charged and convicted of first degree murder with special circumstances of torture. Pearl Fernandez was sentenced to life imprisonment without the possibility of parole and Isauro Aguirre was sentenced to death.\n\nThroughout Fernandez's eight month stay with his mother and Aguirre, multiple people reported signs of abuse to social workers with the [[Department of Children and Family Services (Los Angeles County)|Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services]] and the [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]]. However, Fernandez was never removed from the household. This led to several concerns over the effectiveness and efficiency of social services in [[Los Angeles County]], and ultimately led to four social workers being criminally charged in [[Los Angeles Superior Court]].\n\n==Abuse==\nIn 2012, Pearl Fernandez, the biological mother of Gabriel Fernandez, was given [[child custody]] of Gabriel, reportedly to gain [[welfare]] benefits. She was given custody in spite of concerns from her family, who had been taking care of Gabriel, that she was neglectful towards other children. Fernandez then was moved in with his mother and her boyfriend, Isauro Aguirre.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Story Behind Netflix's Documentary Series 'The Trials of Gabriel Fernandez' |url=https://time.com/5790549/gabriel-fernandez-netflix-documentary/ |website=Time |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile in the household of Pearl Fernandez and Isauro Aguirre for eight months, Gabriel Fernandez was systematically [[child abuse|abused]] and tortured.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web |title=8 times Gabriel Fernandez pleaded for help - from telling teacher he was shot & punched to showing guard horror injuries |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/510383/8-times-gabriel-fernandez-pleaded-for-help-from-telling-teacher-he-was-shot-punched-to-showing-guard-horror-injuries/ |website=The US Sun |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |language=en-us |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The abuse included being forced to eat [[cat litter]] and feces, forced to eat his own vomit, regularly beaten which caused broken bones, burned in various parts of the body, shot in various areas of the body including the face and groin with a BB gun, forced to wear female clothing, forced to sleep bound and gagged in a small cupboard, pepper sprayed, burned with cigarettes, given cold baths, and forced to eat spoiled or expired food.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |title=Who is Gabriel Fernandez's mother Pearl Fernandez? |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/484031/what-happened-to-pearl-fernandez-and-isauro-aguirre-gabriel-fernandezs-killers-featured-in-netflix-documentary/ |website=The US Sun |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en-us |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title='Trials of Gabriel Fernandez': 9 Most Shocking Details About the Murder at Heart of Netflix Documentary |url=https://www.thewrap.com/trials-of-gabriel-fernandez-most-shocking-details-netflix/ |website=TheWrap |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web |title=Everything to Know About Gabriel Fernandez's Tragic Abuse Case Examined in Netflix Docuseries |url=https://people.com/crime/gabriel-fernandez-everything-to-know-abuse-case-netflix-docuseries/ |website=PEOPLE.com |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> According to Fernandez's siblings, while Fernandez was being abused his parents would laugh.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Aguirre reportedly abused Fernandez because he believed he was homosexual; there is no evidence that Fernandez was in fact homosexual. The abuse did not extend to Fernandez's siblings.<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n\n===Death===\n[[File:Childrenshospitallosangeles.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|[[Childrens Hospital Los Angeles]] where Gabriel Fernandez died.]]\n\nOn May 22, 2013, Pearl Fernandez called [[9-1-1]] to report that her child, Gabriel Fernandez, was not breathing.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |title=What happened to Gabriel Fernandez? The true story of his death? |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/468662/what-happened-to-gabriel-fernandez-the-true-story-of-his-death/ |website=The US Sun |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en-us |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Fernandez had been fatally beaten by his mother and Aguirre after failing to clean up his toys. When first responders arrived, they found him on the ground naked with several injuries.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Aguirre explained to them that Fernandez was \"gay\".<ref name=\"auto\"/> Paramedics rushed him to the hospital where doctors declared him [[brain dead]]. He passed away two days later on May 24, 2013 at the [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> He died at the age of eight years, and the official autopsy declared he died of [[blunt force trauma]] coincided with [[neglect]] and [[malnutrition]].\n\n==Victim==\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   =\n| name               =Gabriel Fernandez <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_upright      =\n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            =\n| native_name        =\n| native_name_lang   =\n| pronunciation      =\n| birth_name         = Gabriel Fernandez<!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         =  {{Birth date|2005|02|20}}\n| birth_place        =\n| baptised           = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  =\n| disappeared_status =\n| death_date         =  {{Death date and age|2013|05|24|2005|02|21}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Blunt force trauma]] coincided with [[malnutrition]] and [[neglect]]\n| body_discovered    =\n| resting_place      =\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates (displays \"Burial place\" as label) -->\n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          =\n| nationality        =\n| other_names        =\n| siglum             =\n| citizenship        =\n| education          =  Summerwind Elementary School\n| alma_mater         =\n| occupation         =\n| years_active       =\n| era                =\n| employer           =\n| organization       =\n| agent = <!-- Discouraged in most cases, specifically when promotional, and requiring a reliable source -->\n| known_for          =\n| notable_works      = <!-- produces label \"Notable work\"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label \"Notable credit(s)\"; or by |works=, which produces label \"Works\"; or by |label_name=, which produces label \"Label(s)\" -->\n| style              =\n| home_town          =\n| net_worth          = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             = <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\" or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         =\n| title              = <!-- Formal/awarded/job title. The parameter |office=may be used as an alternative when the label is better rendered as \"Office\" (e.g. public office or appointments) -->\n| term               =\n| predecessor        =\n| successor          =\n| party              =\n| movement           =\n| opponents          =\n| boards             =\n| criminal_charges   = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    =\n| spouse             = <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           =\n| parents            = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             = Pearl Fernandez<!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             =Arnold Contreras<!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          =\n| family             = Isauro Aguirre (''de facto'' stepfather)\n| callsign           =\n| awards             =\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             =\n| module2            =\n| module3            =\n| module4            =\n| module5            =\n| module6            =\n| signature          =\n| signature_size     =\n| signature_alt      =\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n'''Gabriel Fernandez''' (also spelled '''Gabrieal''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.invisiblechildren.org/tag/isauro-aguirre/|title=isauro aguirre &#124; INVISIBLE CHILDREN}}</ref> was born on February 20, 2005<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitchell |first1=Molli |title=Gabriel Fernandez: Who is Michael Lemos Carranza? What happened to him? |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1250625/Gabriel-Fernandez-who-is-Michael-Lemos-Carranza-what-happened-Gabriel-great-uncle-Netflix |website=Express.co.uk |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |language=en |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> to Arnold Contreras and Pearl Fernandez. Shortly after birth, Fernandez was put in the custody of his great-uncle on his mother\u2019s side, Michael Lemos Carranza, and his partner David Martinez. They continued to raise Fernandez for four years. In 2009, four-year-old Gabriel moved in with his grandparents, due to his grandfather's objection to Carranza\u2019s and Martinez\u2019s same-sex relationship. He lived with his grandparents until 2012, when custody of him was given to his mother Pearl Fernandez and her boyfriend Isauro Aguirre, despite concerns for his welfare expressed by the family. Throughout his eight month stay in the household, Fernandez was abused and tortured. On May 22, 2013, Pearl Fernandez and Isauro Aguirre severely beat Gabriel and he was transported to the hospital by emergency services. He was declared [[brain dead]] and taken off life support at [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]] on May 24, 2013. His official autopsy declared his cause of death to be [[blunt force trauma]] commingled with malnutrition and neglect. At the time of his death he was 4 feet 1 inch tall and weighed 56 pounds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Who is Gabriel Fernandez's mother Pearl Fernandez? |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/484031/what-happened-to-pearl-fernandez-and-isauro-aguirre-gabriel-fernandezs-killers-featured-in-netflix-documentary/ |website=The US Sun |language=en-us |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFernandez had two siblings and attended first grade at Summerwind Elementary School, where his teacher was Jennifer Garcia. Garcia described Fernandez as a kind child who enjoyed attending school.\n\n==Perpetrators==\n===Pearl Fernandez===\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Pearl Fernandez\n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Mug shot of Pearl Fernandez.png\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Mug shot of Pearl Fernandez\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Biographical data|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}\n| birth_name = Pearl Sinthia Fernandez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|08|29|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| disappeared_date = \n| disappeared_place = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| home_town = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| height = \n| television = \n| title = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| movement = \n| opponents = \n| boards = \n| criminal_charge = [[First degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] without the possibility of [[parole]]\n| conviction_status = \n| spouse = <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children = 5, including Gabriel    <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = <!-- (as above) -->\n| relatives = \n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance = <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] (only?) -->\n| motive = \n| conviction = February 15, 2018 (pleaded guilty)\n| trial = <!-- Only use this if the trial is bluelinked, e.g. Mafia Commission Trial -->\n| trial_start = \n| trial_end = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = Isauro Aguirre (2010\u201313)\n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = Gabriel Fernandez\n| date = May 22, 2013\n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| endyear = \n| country = \n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned = [[Central California Women's Facility]]\n| module = \n| signature = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = {{collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n'''Pearl Sinthia Fernandez''' was born on August 29, 1983 to Robert and Sandra Fernandez.<ref>{{cite web |last1=EST |first1=Samuel Spencer On 2/28/20 at 8:53 AM |title=What happened to Gabriel Fernandez's grandparents? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trials-gabriel-fernandez-granparents-grandmother-grandfather-robert-sandra-fernandez-netflix-1489703 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Biswas |first1=Shuvrajit Das |title=Where is Pearl Fernandez Now? Gabriel Fernandez's Mother Today |url=https://www.thecinemaholic.com/where-is-pearl-fernandez-now/ |website=The Cinemaholic |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Warnock |first1=Caroline |title=Pearl Fernandez, Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s Mother: 5 Fast Facts |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/02/pearl-fernandez-gabriel-fernandez-mother/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> During her childhood her father was in and out of jail, and Fernandez has claimed that her mother did not love her and would hit her as a child. At the age of nine, Fernandez began using [[methamphetamine]] and drinking [[alcohol drink|alcohol]], and at the age of eleven Fernandez decided to run away from home. She dropped out of school in the 8th grade. As a teenager, Fernandez claimed that her uncle attempted to [[rape]] her, and that some men had held her hostage for a period of days taking turns raping her, which led to her having suicidal thoughts while at the hospital recovering. She has four children with Arnold Contreras, including Gabriel. When Gabriel was born she abandoned him at the hospital three days after his birth; however, she regained custody of Gabriel in 2012. Additionally, she claims that many of her romantic partners, including Aguirre, were abusive to her. However, Elizabeth Carranza, Fernandez's aunt, and her husband claim that Fernandez falsely portrays herself as a victim, and that it was Fernandez who was abusive and controlling towards her romantic partners. Additionally, Fernandez had pending charges against her for threatening to stab Arnold  Contreras. In the months following Gabriel's death, Pearl reported abusing the [[opioid]] drugs [[oxycodone]] and [[Hydrocodone/paracetamol|norco]].<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web |last1=Warnock |first1=Caroline |title=Pearl Fernandez, Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s Mother: 5 Fast Facts |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/02/pearl-fernandez-gabriel-fernandez-mother/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Biswas |first1=Shuvrajit Das |title=Where is Pearl Fernandez Now? Gabriel Fernandez's Mother Today |url=https://www.thecinemaholic.com/where-is-pearl-fernandez-now/ |website=The Cinemaholic |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What Happened To Pearl Fernandez? An Update On What's Happened To Gabriel Fernandez's Mom Since The Documentary |url=https://www.yourtango.com/2020332322/what-happened-pearl-fernandez-trials-of-gabriel-fernandez |website=YourTango |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFernandez has been diagnosed with several mental health issues including [[depressive disorder]], [[developmental disability]], a possible [[personality disorder]], and [[post traumatic stress disorder]]. In 2011, Fernandez took a cognitive ability test, scoring in the 3rd percentile in the verbal comprehension portion of the test, which is on par with a typical second-grade student. Clinical psychologist Deborah S. Miora stated that Fernandez is \"virtually unable to use thought to guide her behavior and temper her emotional reactions.\"<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nCurrently, Fernandez is serving a life sentence without the possibility of parole for first degree murder with special circumstances of torture at [[Central California Women's Facility]]. She was admitted to the facility on June 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=WG0600 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Isauro Aguirre===\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name = Isauro Aguirre\n| honorific_suffix =\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang =\n| image = Mug shot of Isauro Aguirre.png\n| image_upright =\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption = Mug shot of Isauro Aguirre\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Biographical data|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date =     {{birth date and age|1980|06|13|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place =\n| disappeared_date =\n| disappeared_place =\n| disappeared_status =\n| death_date =     <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| death_cause =\n| body_discovered =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| monuments =\n| residence =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| citizenship =\n| education =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = [[Security guard]], [[caregiver]], driver\n| years_active =\n| employer =\n| organization =\n| agent =\n| known_for =\n| notable_works =\n| style =\n| home_town =\n| salary =\n| net_worth =\n| height =\n| television =\n| title =\n| term =\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| party =\n| movement =\n| opponents =\n| boards =\n| criminal_charge = [[First degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture\n| conviction_penalty = [[Capital punishment in California|Death]]\n| conviction_status =\n| spouse =         <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children =       <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents =        <!-- (as above) -->\n| relatives =\n| callsign =\n| awards =\n| website =\n| allegiance =     <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] (only?) -->\n| motive =\n| conviction = November 15, 2017 (found guilty)\n| trial =          <!-- Only use this if the trial is bluelinked, e.g. Mafia Commission Trial -->\n| trial_start =\n| trial_end =\n| reward_amount =\n| capture_status =\n| wanted_by =\n| partners = Pearl Fernandez (2010\u201313)\n| wanted_since =\n| time_at_large =\n| escaped =\n| escape_end =\n| comments =\n| victims = Gabriel Fernandez\n| date = May 22, 2013\n| time =\n| beginyear =\n| endyear =\n| country =\n| states =\n| locations =\n| targets =\n| fatalities =\n| injuries =\n| weapons =\n| apprehended =\n| imprisoned =[[San Quentin State Prison]]\n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n| footnotes =\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n'''Isauro Aguirre''', also known as '''Tony Aguirre''', was born on June 13, 1980.<ref>{{cite web |last1=February 28 |first1=Caroline John-Published: |last2=Am |first2=Caroline John-Published: |title=Isauro Aguirre Wiki: Facts about Pearl Fernandez\u2019s Boyfriend Who Abused Gabriel Fernandez |url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/isauro-aguirre-wiki/ |website=Earn The Necklace |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>  Aguirre repeated two grades in school and ultimately dropped out, implying a possible learning disability.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Warnock |first1=Caroline |title=Isauro Aguirre, Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s Murderer: 5 Fast Facts |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/02/isauro-aguirre-death-row-gabriel-fernandez-murder/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> He worked for Woodland Park Retirement Hotel where he was a caregiver and a driver. Executive director of the retirement home and former boss of Aguirre, Susan Weisbarth, described him as a \"quiet...down to earth nice person, always willing to help.\u201d She also commented that throughout his three year employment he was patient and loving, and would commonly change the diapers of elderly residents at the facility. Staff at the facility nicknamed him \"Shaggy,\" which was, according to Weisbarth, a term referencing his endearment. Ex-coworker Sherline Mille, who also worked for Woodland Park Retirement Hotel, noted that while Aguirre was driving residents he would often drive them the scenic route so they could get to see views other than the freeway. In October 2012, Aguirre began working as a [[security guard]] for AVL Private Security; through AVL he worked at the Vallarta Market in [[Palmdale, California]]. Aguirre met Pearl Fernandez roughly a year and a half to two years before they took custody of Gabriel Fernandez. He is 6 feet 2 inches tall.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |title=Who Is Isauro Aguirre, The Man Who Murdered 8-Year-Old Gabriel Fernandez? |url=https://www.oxygen.com/true-crime-buzz/who-is-isauro-aguirre-the-man-who-murdered-gabriel-fernandez |website=Oxygen Official Site |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAguirre was charged with first degree murder with special circumstances of torture for murdering Gabriel Fernandez. He pleaded not guilty; however, the jury found him guilty and recommended he be sentenced to death, which was accepted by Superior Court Judge George G. Lomeli.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> He was admitted to [[San Quentin State Prison]] on June 13, 2018, where he is currently awaiting execution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=BG5096 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>  However, his execution has yet to be set in accordance with the moratorium on capital punishment issued by California governor [[Gavin Newsom]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=EST |first1=Samuel Spencer On 3/2/20 at 5:29 AM |title=Which prisons are the killers of Gabriel Fernandez in? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trials-gabriel-fernandez-pearl-fernandez-isauro-aguirre-chowchilla-san-quentin-1489967 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Convictions==\nOn May 23, 2013, Pearl Fernandez and Isauro Aguirre were arrested; Fernandez was arrested for felony child endangerment while Aguirre was arrested for attempted murder.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |last1=EST |first1=Samuel Spencer On 2/27/20 at 6:51 AM |title=Where is 'The Trials of Gabriel Fernandez' killer Isauro Aguirre now? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trials-gabriel-fernandez-isauro-aguirre-1489448 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> However, when Gabriel Fernandez died Fernandez and Aguirre were both charged with [[first degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture; prosecutors pursued the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s mother sentenced to life in prison, boyfriend gets death penalty in Palmdale boy\u2019s torture-beating murder |url=https://www.dailynews.com/2018/06/07/gabriel-fernandezs-mother-and-her-boyfriend-to-be-sentenced-today-in-palmdale-boys-torture-beating-murder/ |website=Daily News |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPearl Fernandez plead guilty on February 15, 2018 to her charge as part of a plea deal to avoid the death penalty, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] without the possibility of [[parole]]. In court she stated, \"I want to say I'm sorry for what happened. I wish Gabriel was alive. Every day I wish that I'd made better choices. I'm sorry to my children, and I want them to know that I love them.\"\n===Trial of Isauro Aguirre===\nIsauro Aguirre pleaded not guilty to the charge of [[first degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture, and the case was prosecuted by Deputy District Attorney Jon Hatami and Deputy District Attorney Scott Yang.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Jury Recommends Death Sentence for Isauro Aguirre for Murder of 8-Year-Old Gabriel Fernandez |url=https://ktla.com/news/local-news/jury-recommends-isauro-aguirre-be-sentenced-to-death-for-gabriel-fernandezs-murder/ |website=KTLA |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, jury selection began for the case. Questionnaires were given to prospective jurors, and they were informed that the trial could last as long as six weeks. Additionally, they were told the trial involved \u201cextensive internal and external injuries\u201d of the victim. The jury composition was seven women and five men.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jury selection begins in trial over local boy\u2019s death |url=http://ourweekly.com/news/2017/sep/28/jury-selection-begins-trial-over-local-boys-death/ |website=ourweekly.com |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nWhen the trial began jurors were given details about the extensive abuse Gabriel Fernandez went through in the months preceding his fatal beating. Prosecutor Jon Hatami called Aguirre \"pure evil\" and argued that he deserved the death penalty even though it \"doesn't even compare to what he did to Gabriel.\"\n\nDefense attorney John Alan argued that Aguirre was considered to be \"kind\" and \"compassionate\" during his employment at the retirement facility, and that he had never committed a crime before meeting Pearl Fernandez.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nJury deliberation began on November 14, 2017, and a verdict was reached the next afternoon. Ultimately, the jury found him guilty of first degree murder and guilty of the circumstance of torture charges.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mother\u2019s boyfriend found guilty in systematic torture, murder of 8-year-old boy |url=https://fox17online.com/2017/11/15/mothers-boyfriend-found-guilty-in-systematic-torture-murder-of-8-year-old-boy/ |website=WXMI |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> On December 11, 2017 jury deliberation began for the sentencing phase. The next day the jury was deadlocked; however, on December 13 they decided to recommend the death penalty, which was accepted by Judge George G. Lomeli.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n==Controversy of governmental response==\nIn the months preceding his death, Fernandez showed his injuries or reported abuse to a [[security guard]], family members, and a teacher, which led to several calls to social services to no avail. After being hit with a metal belt, he asked his teacher, Jennifer Garcia, if it's \"normal to bleed.\" In response, Garcia called social services, and was later called by social worker Stefanie Rodriguez informing her that she was assigned to the case. On another day, Fernandez came to class with chunks of hair missing and a lump on his lip. When questioned about it by Garcia, Fernandez said his mother had punched him in his mouth. After having a discussion with the principal, Garcia called Rodriguez back and informed her of the recent signs of abuse. Later when Fernandez reported to his teacher that he was shot in the face with a BB gun by his mother, she once again informed social services of the new sign of abuse. After Fernandez missed thirteen days of school, he returned and his teacher noticed his condition had worsened. She attempted to call Rodriguez, but her call was never returned. Fernandez's great-aunt Elizabeth Carranza and her husband called social services three times and talked to sheriffs twice regarding the welfare of Fernandez. Twenty-nine days before his death, a security guard, Arturo Miranda Martinez, at a Los Angeles County Welfare Office noticed extensive injuries on Fernandez's body which prompted him to call [[9-1-1]], risking his job to report the injuries to sheriffs. Overall, between 2003 and 2012, sixty complaints were filed against Pearl Fernandez and Aguirre to the [[Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services]]. While social workers and the sheriff\u2019s office did check on Fernandez and opened eight independent investigations, he was never removed from the household, ultimately leading to his death.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\nTwo social workers, Stefanie Rodriguez and Patricia Clement, and two supervisors, Kevin Bom and Gregory Merritt for the [[Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services]], were fired and charged with [[child abuse]] and falsifying public records. The unprecedented charges held heavy consequences, including up to eleven years in prison. However, these charges were ultimately dismissed by [[California Courts of Appeal#Second District|California\u2019s 2nd District Court of Appeal]] for lack of probable cause. In January 2020, prosecutors attempted to get a re-hearing for the case, but eventually decided to drop the charges.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nied |first1=Jennifer |title=Gabriel Fernandez's Social Workers Have Another Court Date Coming Up |url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a31741999/gabriel-fernandez-social-workers/ |website=Women's Health |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, 9 Sheriff's deputies were internally disciplined for not properly investigating the abuse allegations.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Christian Community |url=Gloriavale Christian Community |website=Early Christian Doctrines |publisher=Bloomsbury Academic |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Media portrayal ==\n''[[The Trials of Gabriel Fernandez]]'' is a six-part crime documentary that premiered on [[Netflix]] in 2020. Directed by [[Brian Knappenberger]], the documentary details the murder of Gabriel Fernandez.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Portal bar|California|Biography|Law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez, Gabriel}}\n[[Category:2005 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:2013 in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:2013 in media]]\n[[Category:2013 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:May 2013 crimes]]\n[[Category:May 2013 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2010s trials]]\n[[Category:21st century American trials]]\n[[Category:Child abuse in the United States]]\n[[Category:Child abuse resulting in death]]\n[[Category:Criminal investigation]]\n[[Category:Deaths by beating in the United States]]\n[[Category:Legal history of California]]\n[[Category:Murder in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Palmdale, California]]\n[[Category:Violence against children]]\n[[Category:Torture in the United States]]\n[[Category:Psychological abuse]]\n[[Category:Murdered American children]]\n[[Category:Incidents of violence against boys]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2013 murder of an abused eight-year-old American boy}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = Murder of Gabriel Fernandez\n| image                    =\n| caption                  =\n| date                     = {{start date|2013|05|22}} (fatal beating)<br>{{start date|2013|05|24}} (death)\n| time                     =\n| place                    = [[Palmdale, California]], U.S.\n| coordinates              =\n| motive                   = Possibly [[homophobia]]\n| type                     = [[Child abuse]], [[child neglect]]\n| arrests                  = Pearl Fernandez, Isauro Aguirre\n| convicted                = Fernandez, Aguirre\n| sentence                 = [[Life imprisonment]] without [[parole]] (Fernandez) <br /> [[Capital punishment in California|Death]] (Aguirre)\n| charges                  = [[First degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture (both defendents)\n| verdict                  =\n}}\n'''Gabriel Fernandez''' (February 20, 2005 \u2013 May 24, 2013) was an eight-year-old American boy from [[Palmdale, California]], who was abused and tortured over a period of months that ultimately ended in his fatal beating on May 22, 2013. His mother, Pearl Fernandez, and her boyfriend, Isauro Aguirre, were both charged and convicted of first degree murder with special circumstances of torture. Pearl Fernandez was sentenced to life imprisonment without the possibility of parole and Isauro Aguirre was sentenced to death.\n\nThroughout Fernandez's eight month stay with his mother and Aguirre, multiple people reported signs of abuse to social workers with the [[Department of Children and Family Services (Los Angeles County)|Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services]] and the [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]]. However, Fernandez was never removed from the household. This led to several concerns over the effectiveness and efficiency of social services in [[Los Angeles County]], and ultimately led to four social workers being criminally charged in [[Los Angeles Superior Court]].\n\n==Abuse==\nIn 2012, Pearl Fernandez, the biological mother of Gabriel Fernandez, was given [[child custody]] of Gabriel, reportedly to gain [[welfare]] benefits. She was given custody in spite of concerns from her family, who had been taking care of Gabriel, that she was neglectful towards other children. Fernandez then was moved in with his mother and her boyfriend, Isauro Aguirre.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Story Behind Netflix's Documentary Series 'The Trials of Gabriel Fernandez' |url=https://time.com/5790549/gabriel-fernandez-netflix-documentary/ |website=Time |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nWhile in the household of Pearl Fernandez and Isauro Aguirre for eight months, Gabriel Fernandez was systematically [[child abuse|abused]] and tortured.<ref name=\"auto7\">{{cite web |title=8 times Gabriel Fernandez pleaded for help - from telling teacher he was shot & punched to showing guard horror injuries |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/510383/8-times-gabriel-fernandez-pleaded-for-help-from-telling-teacher-he-was-shot-punched-to-showing-guard-horror-injuries/ |website=The US Sun |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |language=en-us |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The abuse included being forced to eat [[cat litter]] and feces, forced to eat his own vomit, regularly beaten which caused broken bones, burned in various parts of the body, shot in various areas of the body including the face and groin with a BB gun, forced to wear female clothing, forced to sleep bound and gagged in a small cupboard, pepper sprayed, burned with cigarettes, given cold baths, and forced to eat spoiled or expired food.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web |title=Who is Gabriel Fernandez's mother Pearl Fernandez? |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/484031/what-happened-to-pearl-fernandez-and-isauro-aguirre-gabriel-fernandezs-killers-featured-in-netflix-documentary/ |website=The US Sun |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en-us |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title='Trials of Gabriel Fernandez': 9 Most Shocking Details About the Murder at Heart of Netflix Documentary |url=https://www.thewrap.com/trials-of-gabriel-fernandez-most-shocking-details-netflix/ |website=TheWrap |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto6\">{{cite web |title=Everything to Know About Gabriel Fernandez's Tragic Abuse Case Examined in Netflix Docuseries |url=https://people.com/crime/gabriel-fernandez-everything-to-know-abuse-case-netflix-docuseries/ |website=PEOPLE.com |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> According to Fernandez's siblings, while Fernandez was being abused his parents would laugh.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Aguirre reportedly abused Fernandez because he believed he was homosexual; there is no evidence that Fernandez was in fact homosexual. The abuse did not extend to Fernandez's siblings.<ref name=\"auto\"/> \n\n===Death===\n[[File:Childrenshospitallosangeles.jpg|thumb|upright=0.8|[[Childrens Hospital Los Angeles]] where Gabriel Fernandez died.]]\nOn May 22, 2013, Pearl Fernandez called [[9-1-1]] to report that her child, Gabriel Fernandez, was not breathing.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web |title=What happened to Gabriel Fernandez? The true story of his death? |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/468662/what-happened-to-gabriel-fernandez-the-true-story-of-his-death/ |website=The US Sun |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en-us |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Fernandez had been fatally beaten by his mother and Aguirre after failing to clean up his toys. When first responders arrived, they found him on the ground naked with several injuries.<ref name=\"auto6\"/> Aguirre explained to them that Fernandez was \"gay.\"<ref name=\"auto\"/> Paramedics rushed him to the hospital where doctors declared him [[brain dead]]. He passed away two days later on May 24, 2013 at the [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]].<ref name=\"auto2\"/> He died at the age of eight years, and the official autopsy declared he died of [[blunt force trauma]] coincided with [[neglect]] and [[malnutrition]].\n\n==Victim==\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   =\n| name               =Gabriel Fernandez <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| honorific_suffix   =\n| image              = <!-- filename only, no \"File:\" or \"Image:\" prefix, and no enclosing [[brackets]] -->\n| image_upright      =\n| landscape          = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            =\n| native_name        =\n| native_name_lang   =\n| pronunciation      =\n| birth_name         = Gabriel Fernandez<!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         =  {{Birth date|2005|02|20}}\n| birth_place        =\n| baptised           = <!-- will not display if birth_date is entered -->\n| disappeared_date   = <!-- {{Disappeared date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (disappeared date then birth date) -->\n| disappeared_place  =\n| disappeared_status =\n| death_date         =  {{Death date and age|2013|05|24|2005|02|21}}\n| death_place        = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause        = [[Blunt force trauma]] coincided with [[malnutrition]] and [[neglect]]\n| body_discovered    =\n| resting_place      =\n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates (displays \"Burial place\" as label) -->\n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| monuments          =\n| nationality        =\n| other_names        =\n| siglum             =\n| citizenship        =\n| education          =  Summerwind Elementary School\n| alma_mater         =\n| occupation         =\n| years_active       =\n| era                =\n| employer           =\n| organization       =\n| agent = <!-- Discouraged in most cases, specifically when promotional, and requiring a reliable source -->\n| known_for          =\n| notable_works      = <!-- produces label \"Notable work\"; may be overridden by |credits=, which produces label \"Notable credit(s)\"; or by |works=, which produces label \"Works\"; or by |label_name=, which produces label \"Label(s)\" -->\n| style              =\n| home_town          =\n| net_worth          = <!-- Net worth should be supported with a citation from a reliable source -->\n| height             = <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\" or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         =\n| title              = <!-- Formal/awarded/job title. The parameter |office=may be used as an alternative when the label is better rendered as \"Office\" (e.g. public office or appointments) -->\n| term               =\n| predecessor        =\n| successor          =\n| party              =\n| movement           =\n| opponents          =\n| boards             =\n| criminal_charges   = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    =\n| spouse             = <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           =\n| parents            = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             = Pearl Fernandez<!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             =Arnold Contreras<!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          =\n| family             = Isauro Aguirre (''de facto'' stepfather)\n| callsign           =\n| awards             =\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             =\n| module2            =\n| module3            =\n| module4            =\n| module5            =\n| module6            =\n| signature          =\n| signature_size     =\n| signature_alt      =\n| footnotes          =\n}}\n'''Gabriel Fernandez''' (also spelled '''Gabrieal''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.invisiblechildren.org/tag/isauro-aguirre/|title=isauro aguirre &#124; INVISIBLE CHILDREN}}</ref> was born on February 20, 2005<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mitchell |first1=Molli |title=Gabriel Fernandez: Who is Michael Lemos Carranza? What happened to him? |url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1250625/Gabriel-Fernandez-who-is-Michael-Lemos-Carranza-what-happened-Gabriel-great-uncle-Netflix |website=Express.co.uk |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |language=en |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref> to Arnold Contreras and Pearl Fernandez. Shortly after birth, Fernandez was put in the custody of his great-uncle on his mother\u2019s side, Michael Lemos Carranza, and his partner David Martinez. They continued to raise Fernandez for four years. In 2009, four-year-old Gabriel moved in with his grandparents, due to his grandfather's objection to Carranza\u2019s and Martinez\u2019s same-sex relationship. He lived with his grandparents until 2012, when custody of him was given to his mother Pearl Fernandez and her boyfriend Isauro Aguirre, despite concerns for his welfare expressed by the family. Throughout his eight month stay in the household, Fernandez was abused and tortured. On May 22, 2013, Pearl Fernandez and Isauro Aguirre severely beat Gabriel and he was transported to the hospital by emergency services. He was declared [[brain dead]] and taken off life support at [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]] on May 24, 2013. His official autopsy declared his cause of death to be [[blunt force trauma]] commingled with malnutrition and neglect. At the time of his death he was 4 feet 1 inch tall and weighed 56 pounds.<ref>{{cite web |title=Who is Gabriel Fernandez's mother Pearl Fernandez? |url=https://www.the-sun.com/news/484031/what-happened-to-pearl-fernandez-and-isauro-aguirre-gabriel-fernandezs-killers-featured-in-netflix-documentary/ |website=The US Sun |language=en-us |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFernandez had two siblings and attended first grade at Summerwind Elementary School, where his teacher was Jennifer Garcia. Garcia described Fernandez as a kind child who enjoyed attending school.\n\n==Perpetrators==\n===Pearl Fernandez===\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name = Pearl Fernandez\n| honorific_suffix = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Mug shot of Pearl Fernandez.png\n| image_upright = \n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = Mug shot of Pearl Fernandez\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Biographical data|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}\n| birth_name = Pearl Sinthia Fernandez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1983|08|29|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place = \n| disappeared_date = \n| disappeared_place = \n| disappeared_status = \n| death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place = \n| death_cause = \n| body_discovered = \n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = \n| monuments = \n| residence = \n| nationality = \n| other_names = \n| citizenship = \n| education = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| years_active = \n| employer = \n| organization = \n| agent = \n| known_for = \n| notable_works = \n| style = \n| home_town = \n| salary = \n| net_worth = \n| height = \n| television = \n| title = \n| term = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| party = \n| movement = \n| opponents = \n| boards = \n| criminal_charge = [[First degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture\n| conviction_penalty = [[Life imprisonment]] without the possibility of [[parole]]\n| conviction_status = \n| spouse = <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children = 5, including Gabriel    <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents = <!-- (as above) -->\n| relatives = \n| callsign = \n| awards = \n| website = \n| allegiance = <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] (only?) -->\n| motive = \n| conviction = February 15, 2018 (pleaded guilty)\n| trial = <!-- Only use this if the trial is bluelinked, e.g. Mafia Commission Trial -->\n| trial_start = \n| trial_end = \n| reward_amount = \n| capture_status = \n| wanted_by = \n| partners = Isauro Aguirre (2010\u201313)\n| wanted_since = \n| time_at_large = \n| escaped = \n| escape_end = \n| comments = \n| victims = Gabriel Fernandez\n| date = May 22, 2013\n| time = \n| beginyear = \n| endyear = \n| country = \n| states = \n| locations = \n| targets = \n| fatalities = \n| injuries = \n| weapons = \n| apprehended = \n| imprisoned = [[Central California Women's Facility]]\n| module = \n| signature = \n| signature_size = \n| signature_alt = \n| footnotes = {{collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n'''Pearl Sinthia Fernandez''' was born on August 29, 1983 to Robert and Sandra Fernandez.<ref>{{cite web |last1=EST |first1=Samuel Spencer On 2/28/20 at 8:53 AM |title=What happened to Gabriel Fernandez's grandparents? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trials-gabriel-fernandez-granparents-grandmother-grandfather-robert-sandra-fernandez-netflix-1489703 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Biswas |first1=Shuvrajit Das |title=Where is Pearl Fernandez Now? Gabriel Fernandez's Mother Today |url=https://www.thecinemaholic.com/where-is-pearl-fernandez-now/ |website=The Cinemaholic |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Warnock |first1=Caroline |title=Pearl Fernandez, Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s Mother: 5 Fast Facts |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/02/pearl-fernandez-gabriel-fernandez-mother/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> During her childhood her father was in and out of jail, and Fernandez has claimed that her mother did not love her and would hit her as a child. At the age of nine, Fernandez began using [[methamphetamine]] and drinking [[alcohol drink|alcohol]], and at the age of eleven Fernandez decided to run away from home. She dropped out of school in the 8th grade. As a teenager, Fernandez claimed that her uncle attempted to [[rape]] her, and that some men had held her hostage for a period of days taking turns raping her, which led to her having suicidal thoughts while at the hospital recovering. She has four children with Arnold Contreras, including Gabriel. When Gabriel was born she abandoned him at the hospital three days after his birth; however, she regained custody of Gabriel in 2012. Additionally, she claims that many of her romantic partners, including Aguirre, were abusive to her. However, Elizabeth Carranza, Fernandez's aunt, and her husband claim that Fernandez falsely portrays herself as a victim, and that it was Fernandez who was abusive and controlling towards her romantic partners. Additionally, Fernandez had pending charges against her for threatening to stab Arnold  Contreras. In the months following Gabriel's death, Pearl reported abusing the [[opioid]] drugs [[oxycodone]] and [[Hydrocodone/paracetamol|norco]].<ref name=\"auto3\"/><ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web |last1=Warnock |first1=Caroline |title=Pearl Fernandez, Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s Mother: 5 Fast Facts |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/02/pearl-fernandez-gabriel-fernandez-mother/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Biswas |first1=Shuvrajit Das |title=Where is Pearl Fernandez Now? Gabriel Fernandez's Mother Today |url=https://www.thecinemaholic.com/where-is-pearl-fernandez-now/ |website=The Cinemaholic |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What Happened To Pearl Fernandez? An Update On What's Happened To Gabriel Fernandez's Mom Since The Documentary |url=https://www.yourtango.com/2020332322/what-happened-pearl-fernandez-trials-of-gabriel-fernandez |website=YourTango |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFernandez has been diagnosed with several mental health issues including [[depressive disorder]], [[developmental disability]], a possible [[personality disorder]], and [[post traumatic stress disorder]]. In 2011, Fernandez took a cognitive ability test, scoring in the 3rd percentile in the verbal comprehension portion of the test, which is on par with a typical second-grade student. Clinical psychologist Deborah S. Miora stated that Fernandez is \"virtually unable to use thought to guide her behavior and temper her emotional reactions.\"<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\nCurrently, Fernandez is serving a life sentence without the possibility of parole for first degree murder with special circumstances of torture at [[Central California Women's Facility]]. She was admitted to the facility on June 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=WG0600 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Isauro Aguirre===\n{{Infobox criminal\n| honorific_prefix =\n| name = Isauro Aguirre\n| honorific_suffix =\n| native_name =\n| native_name_lang =\n| image = Mug shot of Isauro Aguirre.png\n| image_upright =\n| image_size =\n| alt =\n| caption = Mug shot of Isauro Aguirre\n{{collapsed infobox section begin|Biographical data|titlestyle=background-color:#eee}}\n| birth_name =\n| birth_date =     {{birth date and age|1980|06|13|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place =\n| disappeared_date =\n| disappeared_place =\n| disappeared_status =\n| death_date =     <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place =\n| death_cause =\n| body_discovered =\n| resting_place =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| monuments =\n| residence =\n| nationality =\n| other_names =\n| citizenship =\n| education =\n| alma_mater =\n| occupation = [[Security guard]], [[caregiver]], driver\n| years_active =\n| employer =\n| organization =\n| agent =\n| known_for =\n| notable_works =\n| style =\n| home_town =\n| salary =\n| net_worth =\n| height =\n| television =\n| title =\n| term =\n| predecessor =\n| successor =\n| party =\n| movement =\n| opponents =\n| boards =\n| criminal_charge = [[First degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture\n| conviction_penalty = [[Capital punishment in California|Death]]\n| conviction_status =\n| spouse =         <!-- Do not include unless notable or relevant to the crime involved -->\n| children =       <!-- (as above) -->\n| parents =        <!-- (as above) -->\n| relatives =\n| callsign =\n| awards =\n| website =\n| allegiance =     <!-- [[Lucchese crime family]] (only?) -->\n| motive =\n| conviction = November 15, 2017 (found guilty)\n| trial =          <!-- Only use this if the trial is bluelinked, e.g. Mafia Commission Trial -->\n| trial_start =\n| trial_end =\n| reward_amount =\n| capture_status =\n| wanted_by =\n| partners = Pearl Fernandez (2010\u201313)\n| wanted_since =\n| time_at_large =\n| escaped =\n| escape_end =\n| comments =\n| victims = Gabriel Fernandez\n| date = May 22, 2013\n| time =\n| beginyear =\n| endyear =\n| country =\n| states =\n| locations =\n| targets =\n| fatalities =\n| injuries =\n| weapons =\n| apprehended =\n| imprisoned =[[San Quentin State Prison]]\n| module =\n| signature =\n| signature_size =\n| signature_alt =\n| footnotes =\n{{collapsed infobox section end}}\n}}\n'''Isauro Aguirre''', also known as '''Tony Aguirre''', was born on June 13, 1980.<ref>{{cite web |last1=February 28 |first1=Caroline John-Published: |last2=Am |first2=Caroline John-Published: |title=Isauro Aguirre Wiki: Facts about Pearl Fernandez\u2019s Boyfriend Who Abused Gabriel Fernandez |url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/isauro-aguirre-wiki/ |website=Earn The Necklace |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |language=en |date=February 28, 2020}}</ref>  Aguirre repeated two grades in school and ultimately dropped out, implying a possible learning disability.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Warnock |first1=Caroline |title=Isauro Aguirre, Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s Murderer: 5 Fast Facts |url=https://heavy.com/entertainment/2020/02/isauro-aguirre-death-row-gabriel-fernandez-murder/ |website=Heavy.com |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> He worked for Woodland Park Retirement Hotel where he was a caregiver and a driver. Executive director of the retirement home and former boss of Aguirre, Susan Weisbarth, described him as a \"quiet...down to earth nice person, always willing to help.\u201d She also commented that throughout his three year employment he was patient and loving, and would commonly change the diapers of elderly residents at the facility. Staff at the facility nicknamed him \"Shaggy,\" which was, according to Weisbarth, a term referencing his endearment. Ex-coworker Sherline Mille, who also worked for Woodland Park Retirement Hotel, noted that while Aguirre was driving residents he would often drive them the scenic route so they could get to see views other than the freeway. In October 2012, Aguirre began working as a [[security guard]] for AVL Private Security; through AVL he worked at the Vallarta Market in [[Palmdale, California]]. Aguirre met Pearl Fernandez roughly a year and a half to two years before they took custody of Gabriel Fernandez. He is 6 feet 2 inches tall.<ref name=\"auto8\">{{cite web |title=Who Is Isauro Aguirre, The Man Who Murdered 8-Year-Old Gabriel Fernandez? |url=https://www.oxygen.com/true-crime-buzz/who-is-isauro-aguirre-the-man-who-murdered-gabriel-fernandez |website=Oxygen Official Site |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAguirre was charged with first degree murder with special circumstances of torture for murdering Gabriel Fernandez. He pleaded not guilty; however, the jury found him guilty and recommended he be sentenced to death, which was accepted by Superior Court Judge George G. Lomeli.<ref name=\"auto8\"/> He was admitted to [[San Quentin State Prison]] on June 13, 2018, where he is currently awaiting execution.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://inmatelocator.cdcr.ca.gov/Details.aspx?ID=BG5096 |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>  However, his execution has yet to be set in accordance with the moratorium on capital punishment issued by California governor [[Gavin Newsom]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=EST |first1=Samuel Spencer On 3/2/20 at 5:29 AM |title=Which prisons are the killers of Gabriel Fernandez in? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trials-gabriel-fernandez-pearl-fernandez-isauro-aguirre-chowchilla-san-quentin-1489967 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Convictions==\nOn May 23, 2013, Pearl Fernandez and Isauro Aguirre were arrested; Fernandez was arrested for felony child endangerment while Aguirre was arrested for attempted murder.<ref name=\"auto5\">{{cite web |last1=EST |first1=Samuel Spencer On 2/27/20 at 6:51 AM |title=Where is 'The Trials of Gabriel Fernandez' killer Isauro Aguirre now? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/trials-gabriel-fernandez-isauro-aguirre-1489448 |website=Newsweek |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> However, when Gabriel Fernandez died Fernandez and Aguirre were both charged with [[first degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture; prosecutors pursued the death penalty.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gabriel Fernandez\u2019s mother sentenced to life in prison, boyfriend gets death penalty in Palmdale boy\u2019s torture-beating murder |url=https://www.dailynews.com/2018/06/07/gabriel-fernandezs-mother-and-her-boyfriend-to-be-sentenced-today-in-palmdale-boys-torture-beating-murder/ |website=Daily News |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=June 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPearl Fernandez plead guilty on February 15, 2018 to her charge as part of a plea deal to avoid the death penalty, and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] without the possibility of [[parole]]. In court she stated, \"I want to say I'm sorry for what happened. I wish Gabriel was alive. Every day I wish that I'd made better choices. I'm sorry to my children, and I want them to know that I love them.\"\n===Trial of Isauro Aguirre===\nIsauro Aguirre pleaded not guilty to the charge of [[first degree murder]] with special circumstance of torture, and the case was prosecuted by Deputy District Attorney Jon Hatami and Deputy District Attorney Scott Yang.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web |title=Jury Recommends Death Sentence for Isauro Aguirre for Murder of 8-Year-Old Gabriel Fernandez |url=https://ktla.com/news/local-news/jury-recommends-isauro-aguirre-be-sentenced-to-death-for-gabriel-fernandezs-murder/ |website=KTLA |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, jury selection began for the case. Questionnaires were given to prospective jurors, and they were informed that the trial could last as long as six weeks. Additionally, they were told the trial involved \u201cextensive internal and external injuries\u201d of the victim. The jury composition was seven women and five men.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jury selection begins in trial over local boy\u2019s death |url=http://ourweekly.com/news/2017/sep/28/jury-selection-begins-trial-over-local-boys-death/ |website=ourweekly.com |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nWhen the trial began jurors were given details about the extensive abuse Gabriel Fernandez went through in the months preceding his fatal beating. Prosecutor Jon Hatami called Aguirre \"pure evil\" and argued that he deserved the death penalty even though it \"doesn't even compare to what he did to Gabriel.\"\n\nDefense attorney John Alan argued that Aguirre was considered to be \"kind\" and \"compassionate\" during his employment at the retirement facility, and that he had never committed a crime before meeting Pearl Fernandez.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\nJury deliberation began on November 14, 2017, and a verdict was reached the next afternoon. Ultimately, the jury found him guilty of first degree murder and guilty of the circumstance of torture charges.<ref>{{cite web |title=Mother\u2019s boyfriend found guilty in systematic torture, murder of 8-year-old boy |url=https://fox17online.com/2017/11/15/mothers-boyfriend-found-guilty-in-systematic-torture-murder-of-8-year-old-boy/ |website=WXMI |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |language=en |date=November 16, 2017}}</ref> On December 11, 2017 jury deliberation began for the sentencing phase. The next day the jury was deadlocked; however, on December 13 they decided to recommend the death penalty, which was accepted by Judge George G. Lomeli.<ref name=\"auto5\"/>\n\n==Controversy of governmental response==\nIn the months preceding his death, Fernandez showed his injuries or reported abuse to a [[security guard]], family members, and a teacher, which led to several calls to social services to no avail. After being hit with a metal belt, he asked his teacher, Jennifer Garcia, if it's \"normal to bleed.\" In response, Garcia called social services, and was later called by social worker Stefanie Rodriguez informing her that she was assigned to the case. On another day, Fernandez came to class with chunks of hair missing and a lump on his lip. When questioned about it by Garcia, Fernandez said his mother had punched him in his mouth. After having a discussion with the principal, Garcia called Rodriguez back and informed her of the recent signs of abuse. Later when Fernandez reported to his teacher that he was shot in the face with a BB gun by his mother, she once again informed social services of the new sign of abuse. After Fernandez missed thirteen days of school, he returned and his teacher noticed his condition had worsened. She attempted to call Rodriguez, but her call was never returned. Fernandez's great-aunt Elizabeth Carranza and her husband called social services three times and talked to sheriffs twice regarding the welfare of Fernandez. Twenty-nine days before his death, a security guard, Arturo Miranda Martinez, at a Los Angeles County Welfare Office noticed extensive injuries on Fernandez's body which prompted him to call [[9-1-1]], risking his job to report the injuries to sheriffs. Overall, between 2003 and 2012, sixty complaints were filed against Pearl Fernandez and Aguirre to the [[Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services]]. While social workers and the sheriff\u2019s office did check on Fernandez and opened eight independent investigations, he was never removed from the household, ultimately leading to his death.<ref name=\"auto7\"/>\n\nTwo social workers, Stefanie Rodriguez and Patricia Clement, and two supervisors, Kevin Bom and Gregory Merritt for the [[Los Angeles County Department of Children and Family Services]], were fired and charged with [[child abuse]] and falsifying public records. The unprecedented charges held heavy consequences, including up to eleven years in prison. However, these charges were ultimately dismissed by [[California Courts of Appeal#Second District|California\u2019s 2nd District Court of Appeal]] for lack of probable cause. In January 2020, prosecutors attempted to get a re-hearing for the case, but eventually decided to drop the charges.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nied |first1=Jennifer |title=Gabriel Fernandez's Social Workers Have Another Court Date Coming Up |url=https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a31741999/gabriel-fernandez-social-workers/ |website=Women's Health |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Additionally, 9 Sheriff's deputies were internally disciplined for not properly investigating the abuse allegations.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Christian Community |url=Gloriavale Christian Community |website=Early Christian Doctrines |publisher=Bloomsbury Academic |accessdate=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Media portrayal ==\n''[[The Trials of Gabriel Fernandez]]'' is a six-part crime documentary that premiered on [[Netflix]] in 2020. Directed by [[Brian Knappenberger]], the documentary details the murder of Gabriel Fernandez.\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Portal bar|California|Biography|Law}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fernandez, Gabriel}}\n[[Category:2005 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:2013 in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:2013 in media]]\n[[Category:2013 murders in the United States]]\n[[Category:May 2013 crimes]]\n[[Category:May 2013 events in the United States]]\n[[Category:2010s trials]]\n[[Category:21st century American trials]]\n[[Category:Child abuse in the United States]]\n[[Category:Child abuse resulting in 